wing on ethnographic data from Sweden and on theory from both anthropology and science and technology studies, she examines how forensic evidence is produced and how it creates social relationships as cases move from crime scene to courtroom. She demonstrates that forensic evidence is neither a fixed entity nor solely material, but is inseparably part of and made through particular legal, social, and technological practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCriminal investigation. 0aForensic sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  acrime lab.  acrime scene analysis.  acrime scene division.  acrime scene examination.  acrime scene technicians.  acrime scene to courtroom.  acrime.  acriminal investigation division.  acriminal justice work.  acriminal justice.  acriminology.  aevidence handling.  aforensic evidence.  aforensic science.  ahistory of forensics.  alegal evidence.  alitigation.  apolice evidence.  apolice investigations.  aproduction of forensic evidence.  ascience and technology of crime.  ascience and technology studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028838640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096333740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963337423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963337/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY